{{Centurybox|-35}} The '''35th century BC''' in the [[Ancient Near East|Near East]] sees the gradual transition from the [[Chalcolithic]] to the [[Early Bronze Age]]. [[Proto-writing]] enters transitional stage, developing towards [[writing]] proper. [[Wheel]]ed vehicles are now known beyond Mesopotamia, having spread north of the [[Caucasus]] and to [[Europe]].
==Cultures== [[File:Gebelein predynastic mummy British Museum EA 32751.jpg|thumb|alt=EA 32751|The head of EA&nbsp;32751 ("Ginger") showing the preserved hair. Photo taken in 2011.]] * [[Susa]] ([[Iran]] since 7000 BC) * [[Uruk period]] ([[Sumer]]) * [[Naqada]] IIb ([[Ancient Egypt]]) * [[Early Minoan I]] * [[Sredny Stog culture]] (final phase) * [[Yamna culture]] (early phase) * [[Cucuteni culture]] * [[Vinča culture]] * [[Megalith#European_megaliths|Megalithic Europe]] ([[Atlantic fringe]]) * [[Nuragic civilization]] ([[Sardinia]]) * [[Comb Ceramic culture]] * [[Funnelbeaker culture]] * [[Yangshao culture]]
==Artifacts== Only approximate dating is usually possible for mid-4th millennium artifacts. *[[Kish tablet]] *[[Bronocice pot]] *[[Ginger (mummy)]]
==Events==
*The [[Sahara]] desert starts to form from semi-arid [[savanna]]h, through [[desertification]]. *c. 3500 BC: First known zoo at [[Hierakonpolis]]. *c. [[3400 BC]]: [[Sumer]]ian temple record keepers redesign the [[stamp seal]] in the form of a cylinder. *c. 3500 BC: Pictographic [[proto-writing]] starts developing towards writing proper in [[Sumer]], thus starting what is technically considered history. * c. 3500 BC: The first monument of which there is still a trace ({{proper name|Duma na nGiall}}) is built on the [[Hill of Tara]], the ancient seat of the High King of [[Ireland]].<ref>Memory and Monuments at the Hill of Tara by Erin McDonald, Chronika Journal</ref> *c. 3500 BC: [[Tin]] is discovered.
