{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}} {{Infobox UN resolution |number = 505 |organ = SC |date = 26 May |year = 1982 |meeting = 2,368 |code = S/RES/505 |document = https://undocs.org/S/RES/505(1982) |for = 15 |abstention = 0 |against = 0 |subject = {{nowrap|Falkland Islands {{smaller|{{nobold|(''Malvinas'')}}}}}} |result = Adopted |image = |caption = }}
In '''United Nations Security Council resolution 505''', adopted unanimously on 26 May 1982, after reaffirming [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 502|Resolution 502]] (1982) and noting that the situation in the region of the [[Falkland Islands]] had seriously deteriorated, the Council expressed appreciation for the Secretary-General [[Javier Pérez de Cuéllar]]'s efforts to bring about a peaceful solution to the conflict.
The resolution went on to urge both [[Argentina]] and the United Kingdom to cooperate with the Secretary-General to achieve a [[ceasefire]] and, if necessary, to arrange a possible dispatch of United Nations observers to the region to monitor the implementation of a ceasefire. The Council concluded by requesting the Secretary-General to submit a report on developments no later than seven days after the implementation of the resolution.
Several days before the adoption of this resolution, [[Peru]] offered a peace proposal which was rejected by Argentina.<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1665&dat=19820503&id=EWAaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=zSQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5041,129308</ref><ref>http://elcomercio.pe/mundo/actualidad/peru-conflicto-ajeno-nuestra-actuacion-guerra-malvinas-noticia-1395667</ref> Though not included in the final draft, Argentina wished for Resolution 505 to include a reference to a possible interim administration on the islands, an idea that came up in negotiations.<ref>{{cite book|last=Freedman|first=Lawrence|title=The Official History of the Falklands Campaign: War and diplomacy|publisher=Routledge|date=2005|page=526|isbn=978-0-7146-5207-8}}</ref> A further draft resolution by [[Panama]] and Spain was [[United Nations Security Council veto power|vetoed]] by Britain and the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/05/world/un-resolution-on-falkland-war.html|title=UN resolution on Falkland Islands|date=5 June 1982|work=The New York Times}}</ref>
